===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{liushu|p}} of a well or mine with [[cinnabar]] inside. It can also indicate "red cinnabar" used in dyeing clothes (e.g., [[彤]]). The original version is [[𠂁]].

===Etymology 1===
{{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}} suggests a {{w|Kam–Tai languages|Kam-Tai}} origin, comparing it to {{cog|qfa-kms-pro|*h-lanꟲ|t=red}}. {{zh-l|*矸}}, as in {{zh-l|*丹矸}}, may be a variant; see there for more.

Alternatively, it may be from {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*t(j)a-n ~ *tsa-n||red}}, whence {{cog|my|တာ||very red}} ({{zh-ref|Matisoff, 2003}}; {{zh-ref|Hill, 2014}}); however, STEDT currently does not compare this to {{lang|zh|丹}}.

Possibly related to {{och-l|旃|a plain red flag}}, as well as {{och-l|袒|to bare; to strip oneself naked to the waist|id=1}}, as skin color is often associated with "red". See these entries for more.

